entury Hits]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Sunny (Bobby Hebb song)#Remix|Sunny (Remix) 2000]]\" \n| 2000\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014  || 56 || \u2014  || \u2014  || \u2014 || \u2014  || 59 || 80 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Daddy Cool (Boney M. song)|Daddy Cool 2001]]\"\n| 2001\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 47 || \u2014 \n|\n|''[[The Greatest Hits (2001 Boney M. album)|Greatest Hits]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Sunny (Bobby Hebb song)|Sunny]] ([[Mousse T.]] Remix)\"\n| 2006\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 \n|\n|''[[The Magic of Boney M.]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Mary's Boy Child / Oh My Lord\"\n| 2007\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|''[[Christmas with Boney M. (2007)|Christmas with Boney M.]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Felicidad (Margherita)#Felicidad America (Obama-Obama)|Felicidad America (Obama-Obama)]]\"<br /><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring Sherita O. & Yulee B.)</span>\n| 2009\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 \n|align=left|\n|Non-album track\n|-\n| colspan=\"16\" style=\"font-size:90%\" | \"\u2014\" denotes a title that did not chart, or was not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n==Videography==\n* ''Boney M'' VHS Mirror Vision (1981) love for sale concert /with the black African circus in concert - Issued on betamax & video 2000 .\n* ''Gold'' - VHS/VCD (in Hong Kong) (1993)\n* ''Gold'' DVD (2001, Europe)\n* ''Greatest Hits'' (2001, UK)\n* ''Special Edition'' (2002, South Korea)\n* ''Special Edition'' EP (2003, UK)\n* ''The Magic of Boney M.'' (2006)\n* ''Fantastic Boney M. - On Stage and on the Road'' (2007)\n\n==Covers of Boney M. songs==\n* American rock'n'reel group [[Boiled in Lead]] covered \"Rasputin\".\n* Shortly after the worldwide success of the ''[[Nightflight to Venus]]'' album, [[disco]]/[[soul music|soul]] [[singer-songwriter]], [[Millie Jackson]] covered \"Never Change Lovers in the Middle of the Night'\" (a Marcia Barrett lead vocal) for her 1979 album, ''[[A Moment's Pleasure]].'' It was released as a single and became a Top 40 R&B chart hit for Jackson, peaking at #33.\n* \"Silent Lover\" (a Marcia Barrett lead vocal) was covered in 1980 by disco project El Coco for the album \"Revoluci\u00f3n\".\n* [[Gilla (singer)|Gilla]] - also produced by [[Frank Farian]] - covered \"Sunny\", \"No Woman No Cry\" and \"Belfast\" on her album ''Zieh mich aus'' as well as \"Rasputin\" as a single in 1978.\n* In 1978, German singer Bruce Low covered \"Rivers of Babylon\" in German as \"Die Legende von Babylon\", using Boney M.'s original backing track. His version reached #3 in the German charts.\n* Austrian duo and [[Eurovision Song Contest]] participants [[Waterloo & Robinson]] covered \"Brown Girl in the Ring\", using Boney M.'s original backing track (and Marcia Barrett's original \"Tra la la la\" backing vocals).\n* In 1979, [[Michael Holm]] covered \"El Lute\" in German, also using Boney M.'s original backing track with Farian singing backing vocals. His version peaked at #11 in the German charts.\n* [[Roland Kaiser]] also covered \"El Lute\" in German in 1979 as well as a German version of \"I'm Born Again\" under the title \"Im Dunkel der Nacht\".\n* [[Ricky Martin]] covered \"Hooray! Hooray! It's a Holi-Holiday\" in Spanish on his 1993 album ''\"[[Me Amar\u00e1s (album)|Me Amar\u00e1s]]\"''.\n* Frank Farian also produced a German version of \"[[Felicidad (Margherita)]]\" by Anette Anke und Andrea to coincide with Boney M.'s release of the song, 1980.\n* German schlager orchestra Cliff Carpenter's Orchestra made numerous instrumental versions of Boney M.'s hits with a horn section playing the melody line on top of Boney M.'s original backing tracks. In 1982, 12 of these recordings were gathered on the compilation \"Cliff Carpenter Plays Boney M. Hits\".\n* The [[Finnish people|Finnish]] [[folk metal]] band [[Turisas]] have played a cover of \"[[Rasputin (song)|Rasputin]]\" at several live events. They released this cover as their debut single August 2007. They have also released it on a re-release of their album The Varangian Way.\n* UK [[punk rock]] band [[Belisha (band)|Belisha]] have also been covering \"[[Rasputin (song)|Rasputin]]\"  for about 2 years, and riotous live performances at festivals across Europe in 2007 have seen the entire crowd joining in with Russian style dancing, both on stage with the band, and in the audience.\n* [[Placebo (band)|Placebo]] covered \"[[Daddy Cool (Boney M. song)|Daddy Cool]]\" in 2003 for the bonus disc of their ''[[Sleeping with Ghosts]]'' album.\n* [[Peaches (Swedish duo)]] also covered \"[[Daddy Cool (Boney M. song)|Daddy Cool]]\" in 2004.\n* [[Liz Mitchell]] and Russian singer Alexander Buynov covered \"[[Rasputin (song)|Rasputin]]\" in 1996 for a Russian compilation album.\n* [[Marcia Barrett]] did a solo version of \"Rivers of Babylon\" in 2001 which was aired on Dutch radio but ultimately never released.\n* [[Bobby Farrell]] released his own version of 'Baby Do You Wanna Bump' in 2006 on ''The Bump'' EP.\n* The [[Latvian people|Latvian]] [[cello]] [[Trio (music)|trio]] [[Melo-M]] covered \"[[Daddy Cool (Boney M. song)|Daddy Cool]]\" in 2007, featuring [[Maizie Williams]] on vocals (hitting the No.1 spot on the Latvian LMK Charts).\n* The Spanish group [[Fangoria (band)|Fangoria]] recorded a cover version of \"Rasputin\" (sung in Spanish) in 1996 which was also included on BMG-Ariola compilation ''[[Best in Spain]]''.\n* Also on the same ''[[Best in Spain]]'' album, Fangoria singer 'Alaska' sings \"Ma Baker\" (this time in English) with Killer Barbies as backing group.\n* Their song \"[[Ma Baker]]\" has been widely covered. One of the more unusual covers is [[Knorkator]]'s version, which changes the disco/pop tunes for heavy guitar riffs.  According to [[BBC]], the \"Mum-mum-mum-mah\" hook used in the [[Lady Gaga]] song [[Poker Face (Lady Gaga song)|Poker Face]] is sampled from Ma Baker.\"<ref name=bbcchartblog>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/chartblog/2009/03/lady_gaga_poker_face.shtml|title=Lady GaGa - 'Poker Face'|last=McAlpine|first=Fraser|date=2009-03-11|accessdate=2009-03-17|work=[[BBC]]|publisher=[[BBC Online]]}}</ref>\n* Australian children's entertainers [[The Wiggles]] covered \"Brown Girl in the Ring\" on their 2006 album ''Here Comes the Big Red Car''.\n* Techno/rave act Vinylshakerz covered \"Daddy Cool\" on their 2006 album \"Very Superior\".\n* The US ska/punk band [[Sublime (band)|Sublime]] covered \"Rivers of Babylon\" as a Bonus Track on their first album, [[40 Oz. to Freedom]].\n* US Powerpop/Ska band Attila and the Huns recorded a [[reggae]] version of \"[[Mary's Boy Child]]\" based on the Boney M. version for their 2007 Christmas CD \"Christmas Socks\"\n* British ska-punk band [[Sonic Boom Six]] recorded a version of \"Rasputin\" in 2010.\n* Finnish pop/rock/punk band [[Sleepy Sleepers]] covered Rasputin on their 1979 album The Mopott Show. This version is an obscene parody of the original.\n\n==Songs that were re-worked into Boney M. titles==\nFrank Farian's right hand Hans-J\u00f6rg Mayer (aka Georg Reyam) sought out songs from all over the world, mainly public domain (non-copyrighted) folk tunes, and rewrote them for Boney M.\n\n===Borrowed themes===\n* The first Boney M. recording \"[[Baby Do You Wanna Bump]]\" (1975) is based on [[Prince Buster]]'s \"[[Prince Buster#UK Top 40 Singles|Al Capone]]\" (1967).\n* \"[[Love for Sale (Boney M. album)#Track listing|Motherless Child]]\" (1977) is a rewrite of \"[[Sometimes I Feel Like a Motherless Child]]\".\n* \"[[Ma Baker]]\" is a rewrite of a Tunisian traditional song, Sidi Mansur.\n* \"[[Nightflight to Venus#Track listing|Nightflight to Venus]]\" (1978) with its characteristic drums, the rock guitar theme, and the march interludes, was rewritten from [[Cozy Powell]]'s #1 hit \"[[Dance with the Devil (instrumental)|Dance with the Devil]]\" (1974).\n* \"[[Rasputin (song)|Rasputin]]\" (1978) features a melody line present in both a Serbian (\"\u0410\u0458, \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u0441\u0435 \u0446\u0443\u0440\u043e \u0438\u043c\u0430\u0448\") and Turkish traditional (\"\u00dcsk\u00fcdar'a Gider \u0130ken / K\u00e2tibim\").\n* \"[[Nightflight to Venus#Track listing|He Was a Steppenwolf]]\" (1978) borrows arrangement-wise from [[The Temptations]]' lengthy epic \"[[Papa Was a Rollin' Stone]]\" (1972).\n* \"[[Brown Girl in the Ring (song)|Brown Girl in the Ring]]\" (1978) is a traditional Caribbean nursery rhyme and uses an arrangement from [[Malcolm's Locks]] \"Brown Girl\" (1975).\n* \"[[Mary's Boy Child \u2013 Oh My Lord#\"Dancing in the Streets\"|Dancing in the Streets]]\" borrowed the arrangement from the [[Bee Gees]]' \"[[You Should Be Dancing]]\" and the hookline \"Keep on dancing in the streets\" is melodically similar to [[The Beatles]]' \"What's the word I'm thinking of\" \"([[The Word (song)|The Word]])\"\n* \"[[Hooray! Hooray! It's a Holi-Holiday]]\" (1979) is a rewrite of \"[[Polly Wolly Doodle]]\".<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.whosampled.com/cover/view/58421/Boney%20M.-Hooray!%20Hooray!%20It's%20a%20Holi-Holiday_Shirley%20Temple%20and%20Bill%20%22Bojangles%22%20Robinson-Polly%20Wolly%20Doodle%20All%20Day/ |title=Boney M. cover of Shirley Temple and Bill \"Bojangles\" Robinson's 'Polly Wolly Doodle All Day' |website=WhoSampled.com |date= |accessdate=2017-07-19}}</ref>\n* \"[[El Lute / Gotta Go Home (song)#Gotta Go Home|Gotta Go Home]]\" (1979) was a rewrite of German band Nighttrain's \"Hallo Bimmelbahn\" (1973),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=2031988 |title=Images for Nighttrain (2) |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2017-07-19}}</ref> while the middle-part 'Doo-doo-doop, doo doo doo doo doop' (sung by Farian in his head voice) was borrowed from [[The Beatles]] in [[Hello, Goodbye]] (1967) as 'hey-la, hey helloa'.\n* \"[[Oceans of Fantasy#Track listing|No More Chain Gang]]\" (1979) borrows the bridge 'Then one night he laid in waiting' from folklore \"[[St. James Infirmary Blues]]\" and an arrangement inspired by [[Johnny Wakelin]]'s \"In Zaire\" (1976).\n* \"[[I'm Born Again / Bahama Mama (song)|I'm Born Again]]\" (1979) is based on an Irish traditional (\"Buachaill \u00d3n \u00c9irne\").\n* Both \"[[Boonoonoonoos#Track listing|Boonoonoonoos]]\" and \"[[Boonoonoonoos#Track listing|Ride to Agadir]]\" (1981) contain a theme taken from [[Pink Floyd]]'s \"[[Another Brick in the Wall]] (Part 2)\", \"[[The Happiest Days of Our Lives]]\" and \"[[Run Like Hell]]\" (1979).\n* \"[[Boonoonoonoos#Track listing|Train to Skaville / That's Boonoonoonoos]]\" (1981) is partly inspired by the #1 hit [[Pop Muzik]] (1979) by [[M (band)|M]] (the walking bass, the rap parts, and 'Boo-Boo-Boo-Boonoonoonoos' - 'Pop Pop Pop Muzik').\n* \"[[Boonoonoonoos#Track listing|Homeland Africa (Ship Ahoy)]]\" (1981) borrows the chorus and lyrics from [[The O'Jays]]' \"[[Ship Ahoy (album)|Ship Ahoy]]\" (1973).\n* \"[[Children of Paradise/Gadda-Da-Vida|Children of Paradise]]\" (1980) is based on [[Youn\u00e8s M\u00e9gri]]'s \"Lili Twil\" (19??).\n* \"[[Christmas Album (Boney M. album)#Track listing|I'll Be Home for Christmas]]\" (1981) borrows not only the title from the well-known [[I'll Be Home for Christmas|Christmas song]] but also a theme from [[Don Williams]]' \"[[Don Williams#Singles|Some Broken Hearts Never Mend]]\" (1977) and also has a strong resemblance to [[Jona Lewie]]'s \"[[Stop the Cavalry]]\" (1980).\n* \"[[Ten Thousand Lightyears#Track listing|Exodus (Noah's Ark 2001)]]\" (1984) features a guitar theme borrowed from [[The Temptations]]' \"[[Papa Was a Rollin' Stone]]\" (1972) while the chorus borrows from [[Bob Marley]]'s \"[[Exodus (Bob Marley & The Wailers album)#Track listing|Exodus]]\" (1977).\n* \"[[Ten Thousand Lightyears#Track listing|Wild Planet]]\" (1984) is based on Hungarian rock band [[Omega (band)|Omega]]'s \"Ajanlott Utvonal\" (1982) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://forum.sharereactor.ru/showthread.php?t=159412 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214101245/http://forum.sharereactor.ru/showthread.php?t=159412 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-02-14 |title=Boney M. - Full Discography (1975-2009) - \u0424\u043e\u0440\u0443\u043c ShareReactor.ru |publisher=Forum.sharereactor.ru |accessdate=2012-01-04 }}</ref>\n* \"[[Ten Thousand Lightyears#Track listing|Future World]]\" (1984) is based on Hungarian rock band [[Omega (band)|Omega]]'s \"[[10 000 l\u00e9p\u00e9s#Track listing|T\u00edzezer l\u00e9p\u00e9s]]\" (10,000 Steps) (1969).\n* \"[[Ten Thousand Lightyears#Track listing|10 000 Lightyears]]\" (1984) is based on the TV-series \"The Persuaders\" (Germany: Die Zwei (The Two) with Tony Curtis and Roger Moore in the main roles) Theme song composed by John Barry,(1971).\n* \"[[Somewhere in the World]]\" (1984) borrows the hook line from [[Paul McCartney]]'s \"[[Tug of War (Paul McCartney song)|Tug of War]]\" (1982) (the specific chorus line ''In another world'').\n* \"[[Ten Thousand Lightyears#Track listing|Bel Ami]]\" (1984) features an arrangement and brass intro very similar to [[Mezzoforte (band)|Mezzoforte]]'s \"Garden Party\" (1983).\n* \"[[Ten Thousand Lightyears#Track listing|The Alibama]]\" is reworked from a South-African standard \"Daar kom die Alibama.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rBro7dQo8dc |title=Daar kom die Alabama By Sursumkorda |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2017-07-19}}</ref>\n* \"[[Ten Thousand Lightyears#Track listing|Living Like a Moviestar]]\" (1984) features a flute theme from [[Jeff Wayne]]'s \"[[Jeff Wayne's Musical Version of The War of the Worlds#LP|The Eve of the War]]\" (1978).\n* \"[[Eye Dance#Track listing|Todos Buenos]]\" (1985) is rewritten from [[Titanic (band)|Titanic]]'s \"Sultana\" (1971).\n* \"[[Eye Dance#Track listing|Sample City]]\" (1985) features the same chord pattern as \"[[I Can't Stand the Rain (song)|I Can't Stand the Rain]]\" (1973), the [[Ann Peebles]] classic and a 1978 hit single for [[Frank Farian|Farian]]'s soul band [[Eruption (band)|Eruption]].\n* \"[[Bang Bang Lulu#Boney M.|Bang Bang Lulu]]\" (1985) is a traditional folk song.\n\n===Cover versions===\n* \"[[Take the Heat off Me#Track listing|Take the Heat off Me]]\" (1976): [[Marcella Bella]] - \"Nessuno mai\" (1974) <small>([[Gilla (singer)|Gilla]] - \"Mir ist kein Weg zu weit\" (1975))</small>\n* \"[[Sunny (Bobby Hebb song)#Boney M. version|Sunny]]\" (1976): [[Bobby Hebb]] - \"[[Sunny (Bobby Hebb song)|Sunny]]\" (1966)\n* \"[[Take the Heat off Me#Track listing|No Woman No Cry]]\" (1976): [[Bob Marley & The Wailers]] - \"[[No Woman, No Cry]]\" (1974)\n* \"[[Take the Heat off Me#Track listing|Fever]]\" (1976): [[Little Willie John]] - \"[[Fever (1956 song)|Fever]]\" (1956)\n* \"[[Take the Heat off Me#Track listing|Got a Man on My Mind]]\" (1976): [[Frank Farian]] - \"Am Samstagabend\" (1976)\n* \"[[Take the Heat off Me#Track listing|Lovin' or Leavin']]\" (1976): [[Gilla (singer)|Gilla]] - \"Lieben und frei sein\" (1975)\n* \"[[Love for Sale (Boney M. album)#Track listing|Love for Sale]]\" (1977): [[Libby Holman]] - \"Love for Sale\" (1945)\n* \"[[Love for Sale (Boney M. album)#Track listing|Have You Ever Seen the Rain]]\" (1977): [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]] - \"[[Have You Ever Seen the Rain?]]\" (1970)\n* \"[[Love for Sale (Boney M. album)#Track listing|A Woman Can Change a Man]]\" (1977): [[Frank Farian]] and also [[Gilla (singer)|Gilla]] - \"La\u00df mir Zeit, Dich zu lieben\" (1975)\n* \"[[Love for Sale (Boney M. album)#Track listing|Still I'm Sad]]\" (1977): [[The Yardbirds]] - \"[[Having a Rave Up#Track listing|Still I'm Sad]]\" (1965)\n* \"[[Nightflight to Venus#Track listing|Painter Man]]\" (1978): [[The Creation (band)|The Creation]] - \"[[Painter Man]]\" (1966)\n* \"[[Nightflight to Venus#Track listing|King of the Road]]\" (1978): [[Roger Miller]] - \"[[King of the Road (song)|King of the Road]]\" (1965)\n* \"[[Rivers of Babylon]]\" (1978): [[The Melodians]] - \"Rivers of Babylon\" (1970)\n* \"[[Nightflight to Venus#Track listing|Heart of Gold]]\" (1978): [[Neil Young]] - \"[[Heart of Gold (Neil Young song)|Heart of Gold]]\" (1972)\n* \"[[Mary's Boy Child / Oh My Lord (song)|Mary's Boy Child]]\" (1978): [[Harry Belafonte]] - \"[[Mary's Boy Child]]\" (1956)\n* \"[[El Lute / Gotta Go Home (song)#Gotta Go Home|Gotta Go Home]]\" (1979): [[Nighttrain]] - \"Hallo Bimmelbahn\" (1973)\n* \"[[Oceans of Fantasy#Track listing|Hold On I'm Coming]]\" (1979): [[Sam & Dave]] - \"[[Hold On, I'm Comin' (song)|Hold On, I'm Comin']]\" (1966)\n* \"[[Oceans of Fantasy#Track listing|Two of Us]]\" (1979): [[The Beatles]] - \"[[Two of Us (The Beatles song)|Two of Us]]\" (1969)\n* \"My Friend Jack\" (1980): [[The Smoke]] - \"[[The Smoke (English band)#Singles|My Friend Jack]]\" (1967)\n* \"[[In-A-Gadda-Da-Vida (song)#Boney M. version|Gadda-Da-Vida]]\" (1980): [[Iron Butterfly]] - \"[[In-A-Gadda-Da-Vida (song)|In-A-Gadda-Da-Vida]]\" (1968)\n* \"[[Felicidad (Margherita) (song)|Felicidad (Margherita)]]\" (1980): [[Massara]] - \"Margherita\" (1979)\n* \"[[Boonoonoonoos#Track listing|That's Boonoonoonoos / Train to Skaville]]\" (1981): [[The Ethiopians]] - \"Train to Skaville\" (1967)\n* \"[[Boonoonoonoos#Track listing|I Shall Sing]]\" (1981): [[Art Garfunkel]] - \"[[Art Garfunkel#Singles|I Shall Sing]]\" (1973)\n* \"[[Boonoonoonoos#Track listing|Ride to Agadir]]\" (1981): [[Mike Batt]] - \"The Ride to Agadir\" (1977)\n* \"[[Malaika#Boney M. version|Malaika]]\" (1981): [[Miriam Makeba]] & [[Harry Belafonte]] - \"[[Malaika]]\" (1965)\n* \"[[Boonoonoonoos#Track listing|Sad Movies]]\" (1981): [[Sue Thompson]] - \"[[Sad Movies (Make Me Cry)]]\" (1961)\n* \"[[Christmas Album (Boney M. album)#Track listing|Feliz Navidad]]\" (1981): [[Jos\u00e9 Feliciano]] - \"[[Feliz Navidad (song)|Feliz Navidad]]\" (1970)\n* \"[[The Carnival Is Over#Boney M. version|The Carnival Is Over]]\" (1982): [[The Seekers]] - \"[[The Carnival Is Over]]\" (1965)\n* \"[[The Carnival Is Over#Going Back West|Going Back West]]\" (1982): [[Jimmy Cliff]] - \"Going Back West\" (1974)\n* \"[[Jambo Bwana#Boney M. version|Jambo - Hakuna Matata (No Problems)]]\" (1983): [[Them Mushrooms]] - \"[[Jambo Bwana]]\" (1982)\n* \"[[Ten Thousand Lightyears#History|(I Need a) Babysitter]]\" (1983): [[Mahjun]] - \"Baby-sitter\" (1980)\n* \"[[Ten Thousand Lightyears#Track listing|Dizzy]]\" (1984): [[Tommy Roe]] - \"[[Dizzy (Tommy Roe song)|Dizzy]]\" (1969)\n* \"[[Kalimba de Luna#Boney M. version|Kalimba de Luna]]\" (1984): [[Tony Esposito (musician)|Tony Esposito]] - \"[[Kalimba de Luna]]\" (1984)\n* \"[[Happy Song#Boney M. version|Happy Song]]\" (1984): [[Baby's Gang]] - \"[[Happy Song]]\" (1983)\n* \"[[My Cherie Amour (song)|My Ch\u00e9rie Amour]]\" (1985): [[Stevie Wonder]] - \"[[My Cherie Amour (song)|My Cherie Amour]]\" (1969)\n* \"[[Eye Dance#Track listing|Dreadlock Holiday]]\" (1985): [[10cc]] - \"[[Dreadlock Holiday]]\" (1978)\n* \"[[Stories (Boney M. song)|Stories]]\" (1990): [[Izit]] - \"Stories\" (1989)\n* \"[[More Gold - 20 Super Hits Vol. II#Track listing|Time to Remember]]\" (1993): [[La Mama (band)|La Mama]] - \"I'll Be Your Woman\" (1982)\n* \"[[More Gold - 20 Super Hits Vol. II#Track listing|Papa Chico]]\" (1993): [[Tony Esposito (musician)|Tony Esposito]] - \"Papa Chico\" (1985)\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Boney M.}}\n* [[List of best-selling music artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.themagicofboneym.co.uk The Magic Of Boney M] - Unofficial website with discography, history, biography and more.\n\n{{Boney M.}}\n{{Boney M. singles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boney M}}\n[[Category:Boney M.]]\n[[Category:Pop music group discographies]]\n[[Category:Discographies of German artists]]\n", "name_user": "Jo-Jo Eumerus", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Greatest Hits of All Times \u2013 Remix '89 \u2013 Volume IIclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boney_M._discography"}
{"title_page": "The Summer Mega Mix", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Summer Mega Mix\n| cover      = Boney_M._-_The Summer Mega Mix_(1989_single).jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Boney M.]]\n| album      = <br/>Greatest Hits of All Times \u2013 Remix '89 \u2013 Volume II\n| released   = May, 1989\n| format     = [[Gramophone Record|7\" single]], [[Gramophone Record|12\" single]], [[CD-single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Disco]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Hansa Records]] <small>(FRG)</small>\n| composer   =\n| lyricist   =\n| producer   = [[Frank Farian]]\n| prev_title = [[Megamix (Boney M. song)|Megamix]]\n| prev_year  = 1988\n| next_title = [[Malaika#1989 Remix|Malaika (Lambada Remix)]]\n| next_year  = 1989\n}}\n'''\"The Summer Megamix\"''' is a 1989 single by German band [[Boney M.]] The single peaked at #11 in the French charts[http://www.hitparade.ch/showitem.asp?key=266371&cat=s] and #3 in Norway. In the UK, the single barely reached the top 100, peaking only at #92. The megamix is a medley of remixed Boney M. hits, \"[[Sunny (Bobby Hebb song)#Boney M. version|Sunny]]\", \"[[Hooray! Hooray! It's a Holi-Holiday]]\", \"[[Kalimba de Luna]]\", \"[[Ma Baker]]\" and \"[[El Lute / Gotta Go Home|El Lute]]\".  \n\n==Releases==\n7\"<br />\n* \"The Summer Mega Mix\" (Radio Version) - 4:28 / \"The Calendar Song\" (Remix) - 2:20 ([[Hansa Records]] 112 466-100, 1989)\n\n12\"<br /> \n* \"The Summer Mega Mix\" (Extended Version) - 7:25 / \"The Calendar Song\" (Remix) - 2:20 / \"The Summer Mega Mix\" (Radio Version) - 4:28 (Hansa 612 466-213, 1989)\n\nCD\n* \"The Summer Mega Mix\" (Radio Version) - 4:28 / \"The Calendar Song\" (Remix) - 2:20 (Hansa 162 466-203, 1989)\n* \"The Summer Mega Mix\" (Extended Version) - 7:25 / \"The Calendar Song\" (Remix) - 2:20 / \"The Summer Mega Mix\" (Radio Version) - 4:28 (Hansa 662 466-211, 1989)\n\n==Sources==\n*http://www.hitparade.ch/showitem.asp?key=266371&cat=s\n\n{{Boney M. singles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Summer Mega Mix}}\n[[Category:1989 songs]]\n[[Category:Boney M. songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Summer Mega Mix\n| cover      = Boney_M._-_The Summer Mega Mix_(1989_single).jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Boney M.]]\n| album      = <br/>[[Greatest Hits of All Times \u2013 Remix '89 \u2013 Volume II]]\n| released   = May, 1989\n| format     = [[Gramophone Record|7\" single]], [[Gramophone Record|12\" single]], [[CD-single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Disco]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Hansa Records]] <small>(FRG)</small>\n| composer   =\n| lyricist   =\n| producer   = [[Frank Farian]]\n| prev_title = [[Megamix (Boney M. song)|Megamix]]\n| prev_year  = 1988\n| next_title = [[Malaika#1989 Remix|Malaika (Lambada Remix)]]\n| next_year  = 1989\n}}\n'''\"The Summer Megamix\"''' is a 1989 single by German band [[Boney M.]] The single peaked at #11 in the French charts[http://www.hitparade.ch/showitem.asp?key=266371&cat=s] and #3 in Norway. In the UK, the single barely reached the top 100, peaking only at #92. The megamix is a medley of remixed Boney M. hits, \"[[Sunny (Bobby Hebb song)#Boney M. version|Sunny]]\", \"[[Hooray! Hooray! It's a Holi-Holiday]]\", \"[[Kalimba de Luna]]\", \"[[Ma Baker]]\" and \"[[El Lute / Gotta Go Home|El Lute]]\".  \n\n==Releases==\n7\"<br />\n* \"The Summer Mega Mix\" (Radio Version) - 4:28 / \"The Calendar Song\" (Remix) - 2:20 ([[Hansa Records]] 112 466-100, 1989)\n\n12\"<br /> \n* \"The Summer Mega Mix\" (Extended Version) - 7:25 / \"The Calendar Song\" (Remix) - 2:20 / \"The Summer Mega Mix\" (Radio Version) - 4:28 (Hansa 612 466-213, 1989)\n\nCD\n* \"The Summer Mega Mix\" (Radio Version) - 4:28 / \"The Calendar Song\" (Remix) - 2:20 (Hansa 162 466-203, 1989)\n* \"